  "prompt": "If you were born deaf, what language would you think in?",
  "response": "If someone is born deaf, their experience of language can vary widely depending on their exposure to communication methods. Many deaf individuals use sign languages, which are fully developed languages with their own grammar and syntax. Therefore, someone who was born deaf might think in a sign language, visual imagery, or even a mixture of concepts and ideas without relying on spoken language.\n\nAdditionally, individuals may also develop their own personal way of conceptualizing thoughts that may not fit into traditional language structures, drawing on visual experiences, emotions, and abstract concepts. The nuances of thought processes can be unique to each individual based on their environment, education, and personal experiences.",
